_items.body: Colours are represented on a colour wheel. The colour wheel allows us to explore relationships between colours. Black and white, which are more accurately referred to as shades, don’t appear on the wheel.

Warm and cool


The colour wheel is divided into warm and cool colours. The red-orange-yellow part of the wheel evokes warmth, and these colours are a popular choice for bold, statement pieces.


The green-blue-purple range of colours evoke a sense of coolness, and they tend to recede from view. As a result, cool colours are frequently chosen to create a sense of calm.


Paired together, warm and cool colours create a sense of balance.

Harmonious


Colours that are close to each other on the colour wheel – eg blue-purple-red, or shades of the same colour eg shades of blue - are refererred to as harmonious colours. Together, they create harmony and communicate a sense of calm.

Contrasting colours 


Colours that are opposite each other on the colour wheel have a high level of contrast. They make the colour they’re paired with appear even more vibrant. They compete for attention, and make a big impact. High contrast pairs include:


• Red and green

• Blue and orange

• Violet and yellow

• Black and white
